==English==

===Etymology===
From Old Norse ''veikr'' "weak," from Proto-Indo-European base ''*weik-'' "to bend, wind"

===Pronunciation===
*wēk, /wiːk/, /<tt>wi:k</tt>/
*:'''Homophones''': [[week]]
*:[[Rhymes:English:-iːk|Rhymes: -iːk]]

===Adjective===
'''weak'''  ({{compar}}: '''[[weaker]]''', {{superl}}: '''[[weakest]]''')

# Lacking in [[force]] or [[ability]].
# Good or cool ( we had a weak time ) slang in P.E.I., Canada.
# Bad or uncool ( this homework goes weak ) slang in Austin, Texas
# (''Grammar'') [[regular]].
# {{Physics}} One of the four [[fundamental]] [[force]]s associated with [[nuclear]] [[decay]].

